	India to host squash World Cups  
	 New Delhi: India has been awarded World Cup hosting rights by the World Squash Federation (WSF). The decision, taken by WSF in its executive board meeting on Monday, is likely to give the game a major boost in the country.  
	 Spearheaded by the Sports Development Authority of Tamil Nadu (SDAT), the biennial event will be held in Chennai in 2011, 2013 and 2015. The first edition, to be named as SDAT WSF World Cup, will take place next year from March 8-12, a WSF release said.  
	 More cash  
	 Nyon: Uefa has increased cash payments for the clubs involved in the Champions League group-stage. The elite 32 teams are set to get more than euro750 million combined in bonuses, prize money and shares of television rights.   
	 Sesa win  
	 Vasco: A second half goal by striker Lezly Fernandes guided Sesa Football Academy to a 1-0 victory over Vasco Sports Club in the preliminary qualifying knock-out round of the Federation Cup, at the Tilak Stadium here.  
	 CWG boost  
	 Wellington: The New Zealand Olympic Committee rsquo;s apprehension about their players rsquo; safety during the Commonwealth Games notwithstanding, defending 1500metre champion Nick Willis said he is comfortable with the security arrangements put in place for the October 3-14 mega-event.   
	 Dope case  
	 Berlin: A former senior East German sports official has reportedly acknowledged that there was widespread state-sponsored doping in the communist country, including of minors, in a new book. A German news agency reported Tuesday that it obtained Thomas Koehler rsquo;s Two Sides of the Medal ahead of publication this week.   
	 Cyclist ban  
	 Paris: French cyclist Mickael Larpe has been suspended for two years by the French federation after testing positive for the blood-booster EPO.   
	 Nick in  
	 Hinwil: Formula One team Sauber replaced Pedro de la Rosa with Nick Heidfeld on Tuesday, appointing the experienced driver for the remainder of the 2010 season. Heidfeldwill take over for the next race in Singapore.   
	 Latif quits   
	 Islamabad: Rashid Latif resigned on Tuesday as a specialist coach for the PCB after he was asked to explain comments that were critical of the PCB over the match-fixing scandal.  
	 Latif stepped down as wicketkeeping coach at the National Cricket Academy in Lahore after being served with a notice by the PCB to front the board.  
